        "date":  "2026-06-26",
        "theme":  "Strategy",
        "summary":  "Workers save an average of 11 hours weekly through AI tools, but spend 6.4 hours botsitting ΓÇö verifying outputs, debugging mistakes, and managing hallucinations ΓÇö which negates most productivity gains. Organizations lack governance frameworks to define verification requirements and quality standards, so time savings shift as untracked rework for downstream teams. Experts recommend governance frameworks, better AI tool integration, and employee training to convert apparent productivity gains into measurable organizational value.",
        "execSummary":  "This finding is a direct warning for customer-support leaders who have deployed AI tools expecting net efficiency gains: if your agents are spending hours re-checking AI outputs, your ROI calculations are likely overstated. The root cause is absent governance ΓÇö no defined standards for when to trust AI output versus verify it. Leaders should instrument AI workflows to measure actual end-to-end cycle time, not just self-reported time savings. Establishing clear verification standards by task type is the concrete next step.",
        "vendorLean":  "Neutral",
